paragraph.leadIn:
Notwithstanding subrule (2), the Superintendent may permit a prisoner to
                    write and send more than one letter per week at public expense
                            if— (L.N. 150 of 2014)

subparagraph.content:
maintaining the security, good order and discipline of the prison;
                                (L.N. 174 of
                            2025)

paragraph.content:
any matter which depicts, describes, or encourages activities which may
                    lead to the use of physical violence or group disruption inside any
                    prison;

any information on escape plots, plans or other material which tends to
                    assist or encourage the commission of any offence enumerated in rule
                        61 or of any criminal offence;

any information that will infringe the privacy of individual prisoners or
                    of members of the staff of the Correctional Services Department, including
                    information about any of them;

prohibit the prisoner from writing and sending any letter to a legal
                    representative mentioned in rule 52A(5)(a)(i) or (ii)
                            (relevant legal representative);

may only be opened or read in the presence of the prisoner (except where
                    the prisoner indicates that he or she does not wish to be present);
                    and

communicates with another prisoner for an improper purpose or when prohibited
                from doing so in the interests of the discipline of the
                prison;

without reasonable excuse, disfigures or damages any part of the prison or any
                property which is not his
                own;

a person committed to prison in default of payment of a sum adjudged to be
                    paid by a conviction shall be treated as serving a sentence of imprisonment;
                    and

diligently
                observe the behaviour of all subordinate officers and prisoners;
                (E.R. 3 of 2015)

for the information of the Superintendent, enter in a book kept for that
                purpose all directions which he may deem necessary to give relative to the treatment
                of any prisoner not admitted to the hospital;

section.def:
accused (被控者) means a
            Chief Officer, subordinate officer or any other person employed in the prisons who is
            charged with a disciplinary offence;

paragraph.content:
without good and sufficient cause fails
                                                  to carry out any lawful order, whether written or
                                                  verbal;

subparagraph.content:
without proper authority communicates
                                                  with any ex-prisoner or with a relative, or friend
                                                  of any prisoner, or ex-prisoner;

allows any undue familiarity between a
                                                  prisoner and himself, or any other person employed
                                                  in the prisons;

discusses his duties, or any matters of
                                                  discipline or prison arrangement, within the
                                                  hearing of a prisoner;

paragraph.content:
without necessity uses force in dealing
                                                  with the prisoners, or where the use of force is
                                                  necessary, uses undue force;

subparagraph.content:
neglects to report any damage to, or loss
                                                  of, any article of clothing, or personal
                                                  equipment, however caused;

paragraph.content:
any payment, release, discharge or
                                                  liquidation of any loan, obligation or other
